  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "To prevent a sunburn from peeling, it\u2019s essential to focus on hydration, soothing the skin, and promoting healing. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide:\n\n### 1. **Cool the Skin**\n   - **Apply cool compresses**: Use a clean, damp cloth or take a cool shower to reduce heat and inflammation.\n   - **Avoid hot water**: Hot showers or baths can further dry out your skin.\n\n### 2. **Moisturize Regularly**\n   - Use a gentle, fragrance-free moisturizer or aloe vera gel to hydrate the skin. Apply it while your skin is still slightly damp to lock in moisture.\n   - Look for products containing ingredients like hyaluronic acid, ceramides, or glycerin.\n\n### 3. **Stay Hydrated**\n   - Drink plenty of water to help your body heal from within.\n\n### 4. **Use Soothing Products**\n   - Aloe vera gel is excellent for calming sunburned skin and reducing inflammation.\n   - Over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream can help reduce redness and swelling (use as directed).\n\n### 5. **Avoid Further Irritation**\n   - Wear loose, soft clothing to prevent friction on the affected area.\n   - Avoid further sun exposure by staying indoors or using protective clothing and sunscreen.\n\n### 6. **Do Not Pick or Peel**\n   - Resist the urge to peel off flaking skin, as this can lead to infection or scarring. Let it shed naturally.\n\n### 7. **Use Anti-Inflammatory Remedies**\n   - Over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or aspirin can reduce inflammation and discomfort.\n\n### 8. **Consider Natural Remedies**\n   - Oatmeal baths or cold milk compresses can soothe irritated skin.\n\n### 9. **Protect Healing Skin**\n   - Once the sunburn starts to heal, apply a broad-spectrum sunscreen with SPF 30+ to protect the skin from further damage.\n\nIf the sunburn is severe (with blisters, fever, or dizziness), seek medical attention promptly.",
